art form. This book shows how military discourses and early war media such as star charts, horoscopes, and the Prussian wargame were entangled with ideas of creativity, genius, and possible worlds in philosophy and aesthetic theory (by thinkers such as Leibniz, Baumgarten, Kant, and Schiller) in order to trace the emergence of martial aesthetics. Adopting an approach that is simultaneously historical and theoretical, Engberg-Pedersen presents a new frame for understanding war in the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aAesthetics, Moderny21st century. 0aArt and warxHistory. 0aArt and warxPhilosophy. 7aART / Art & Politics.2bisacsh  aAesthetics.  aArt.  aCreativity.  aDesign.  aMedia.  aMilitary Theory.  aPhilosophy.  aTechnology.  aWar.  aWargames.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079132740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363486240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503634862423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503634862/original  a978-3-11-079132-7  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles